  <!-- BLOCK 0 — FOUNDATION -->
  <div class="section" id="foundation">
    <div class="sec-label">Foundation<br>1990s–2000s</div>
    <div class="sec-body">
      <h2>It Starts With the Box.</h2>
      <p>Before critical facilities, before $20 million rebuilds, before AI compute infrastructure — there was a half-pipe. Built solo at age 13 from plans pulled out of Thrasher magazine. No crew. No contractor. Measured, cut, assembled. It held.</p>
      <p>That same logic carried into a career in custom cabinetry and furniture building — where a millimeter off is visible, where the joinery either holds or it doesn't, and where the person doing the work is accountable to the finished product every time someone opens a drawer. From there into custom residential construction alongside Kirk Sanders — one of the most respected custom home builders in the region — learning framing, finish work, and the relationship between a plan on paper and what a building actually requires to stand.</p>
      <p>Luxury apartment construction followed. Same discipline. Larger box. More systems, more coordination, more contractors, more code. Low-voltage, AV, and structured cabling across multi-unit developments where the work had to be right the first time because tenants were moving in behind it.</p>
      <p>The Kemah Boardwalk rebuild after Tropical Storm Allison was the first large-scale infrastructure event — storm damage, compressed timeline, no margin for error on a commercial waterfront property. The work got done. The boardwalk reopened.</p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"It's all just building boxes. Different boxes go inside different boxes."</p>
        <cite>— VanBlake Shannon</cite>
      </div>

      <p>Every decade since has been the same observation applied to a larger, more complex, more consequential box. The cabinetry taught precision. The custom homes taught systems thinking. The commercial builds taught coordination under pressure. None of it was wasted. All of it transferred.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- BLOCK 1 — DOCTRINE -->

  <div class="section" id="doctrine">
    <div class="sec-label">Field<br>Doctrine</div>
    <div class="sec-body">
      <h2>What This Is</h2>
      <p>Van Blake Shannon has been the last line of defense in rooms where failure was not a budget line — it was a body count. Thirty years. Zero fatalities. Zero unplanned shutdowns.</p>
      <p>This document is not a resume. Resumes describe job titles. This describes what those titles required when the situation had no clean answer — and what that record of outcomes means for the next organization that needs someone who has held that standard before.</p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"My value is in the safety, compliance and efficiency blindspot most companies don't even know they have."</p>
        <cite>— VanBlake Shannon</cite>
      </div>

      <p>The blindspot is consistent across industries. The gap between what a facility document says and what is actually installed, operational, and safe is where most organizations are most exposed — and least aware. Thirty years of field work across performing arts, healthcare, property management, and emerging compute infrastructure produced one consistent observation: <strong>compliance on paper is not compliance in reality.</strong></p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"A building's only as smart as its least competent employee or its worst leader."</p>
        <cite>— VanBlake Shannon</cite>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- BLOCK 2 — ALLEY THEATRE -->
  <div class="section" id="alley">
    <div class="sec-label">Alley<br>Theatre<br>Houston</div>
    <div class="sec-body">
      <h2>Where the Standard Was Built</h2>
      <p>The Alley Theatre holds the Special Tony Award for Outstanding Regional Theatre. The American Institute of Architects called it "inside and out, a brilliant theatrical event" — the only brutalist theatre of its era to win the AIA national Honor Award. Productions have transferred to Broadway, Lincoln Center, and the Venice Biennale.</p>
      <p>It occupies a raw concrete landmark in the heart of Houston's Theatre District — designed by architect Ulrich Franzen with no right angles, curved walls wrapping three internal triangles, two stages connected by underground passages, and a four-story scene shop fourteen stories above street level where every set, prop, and costume for every production is built by hand. Backdrops valued at over a million dollars on some runs. The building was never designed for the infrastructure it had to carry. Systems were hidden wherever the architecture allowed.</p>
      <p>Hurricane Harvey exposed every one of those compromises simultaneously.</p>
      <p>Floodwater reached the sub-level infrastructure. A concrete block wall had failed around the frame of a steel door, collapsing into the switchgear room. A damaged sprinkler head continued filling the room independent of the pumps running to clear it. Restoring access required identifying that those two failures were connected before anything else could happen.</p>
      <p>The $20 million rebuild that followed involved Bellows Construction, Britain Electric, and Johnson Controls — contractors with long-standing relationships and no tolerance for shortcuts. Every sensor in the BAS and BMS system was walked and verified with JCI. Every discrepancy between documentation and actual installed conditions was identified and corrected. The Alley conducted its first-ever digital fire extinguisher demonstration with the Houston Fire Department — fire marshal present, full company in attendance. A hurricane preparedness briefing was delivered to more than 200 staff on the Hubbard Stage.</p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"Slow is smooth, smooth is fast."</p>
        <cite>— U.S. Navy SEALs &nbsp;·&nbsp; Applied throughout the Alley Theatre rebuild</cite>
      </div>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"The Alley was an ark of experience and knowledge. I learned something from everyone there."</p>
        <cite>— VanBlake Shannon</cite>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- BLOCK 3 — HEALTHCARE / CBRE -->
  <div class="section" id="healthcare">
    <div class="sec-label">Healthcare<br>&amp; Campus<br>Infrastructure</div>
    <div class="sec-body">
      <h2>When the Floor Cannot Go Dark</h2>
      <p>Healthcare infrastructure operates under a different set of consequences. At Kelsey-Seybold Medical, an ATS transfer switch failed on an active surgical floor. The options were limited. The timeline was immediate. Resolution required working within live electrical systems, NEC compliance under pressure, and the judgment to sequence actions correctly when the margin for error was zero.</p>
      <p>The floor stayed online. No patient impact. No code violations.</p>
      <p>At CBRE's TMC-3 Helix Park campus expansion — one of the most complex medical real estate developments in Texas — the work shifted to scale. Multi-system coordination across active tenant operations. Campus infrastructure planning across buildings that could not stop functioning while new ones came online.</p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"Compliance on paper is not compliance in reality."</p>
        <cite>— VanBlake Shannon</cite>
      </div>

      <p>Both environments reinforced the same finding: the gap between what a facility document says and what is actually installed, operational, and safe is where organizations are most exposed — and the person who can close that gap without stopping operations is the one they cannot afford not to have.</p>

