  <!-- BLOCK 4 — ID34 -->
  <div class="section" id="id34">
    <div class="sec-label">ID34<br>Mining &amp;<br>Engineering</div>
    <div class="sec-body">
      <h2>The Same Discipline. A Smaller Box.</h2>
      <p>In 2022, Shannon co-founded ID34 Mining & Engineering in Houston under the SOETT™ framework — Sustainable Operational Excellence Through Technology. The work applies thirty years of critical infrastructure doctrine directly to emerging compute systems.</p>
      <p>The proof of concept is documented on video: a solar-powered ESP32 solo Bitcoin mining node — edge computing, thermal management, off-grid power — built, deployed, and running. A Phase 1 application was submitted to the DOE Beyond the Meter Energy Storage Integration Prize, addressing heat recovery from compute infrastructure before the AI buildout made it a mainstream conversation. The ID34 Thermal Texas Twin Turbo — a dual-node ESP32 miner in a 3D-printed hexagonal enclosure — is the physical product lane.</p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"It's all just building boxes. Different boxes go inside different boxes."</p>
        <cite>— VanBlake Shannon</cite>
      </div>

      <p>The throughline from the Alley Theatre's BAS system to a solar-powered microcontroller mining Bitcoin in a custom-printed enclosure is not a career pivot. It is the same systems discipline applied to a different scale. OT and ICS security work followed from the same logic — legacy PLC vulnerabilities across Modbus TCP, EtherNet/IP, and S7 protocol represent the same class of problem as a switchgear room filling with water. The failure mode differs. The gap between documented compliance and operational reality is identical.</p>
      <p>Shannon identified the field engineer training gap in AI data centers publicly — on video — months before it surfaced as an industry conversation. The question he raised then remains unanswered at most facilities: how are engineers being trained differently to operate smart infrastructure? At most organizations, they are not.</p>

